WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:05.920
Stretching across the heart of the European&nbsp;
continent, from the Mediterranean Cote d’Azure to

00:00:05.920 --> 00:00:11.840
the banks of the Danube River in Vienna, the&nbsp;
crescent shaped Alps form a roughly 1,200 kilometer 

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:16.800
long fortress, roughly equivalent to the&nbsp;
distance from Chicago to Florida. The 8

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:22.000
countries within and around its domain have&nbsp;
been shaped by the Alps’ summits and valleys,

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:28.080
its glaciers and and its meadows for thousands&nbsp;
of years and to this day, its impenetrability and

00:00:28.080 --> 00:00:33.760
beauty continue to influence the politics&nbsp;
and cultural identity of central Europe.

00:00:33.760 --> 00:00:38.080
To fully understand what makes the Alps&nbsp;
so special for the European continent,

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:43.600
let’s embark on a journey from the coast of the&nbsp;
Ligurian Sea to its transition into the Dinaric

00:00:43.600 --> 00:00:49.600
Alps and the Great Hungarian Plain, looking at how&nbsp;
its peaks and valleys created deep glacial lakes,

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:55.760
strange border quirks, vital trade routes and some&nbsp;
of the world’s most iconic mountain landscapes.

00:00:55.760 --> 00:01:02.800
Chapter 1 - The Western Alps
On Italy’s narrow Ligurian coast, the Western

00:01:02.800 --> 00:01:09.920
Alps begin almost at the water’s edge, rising&nbsp;
sharply behind the last coastal hills. Here, where

00:01:09.920 --> 00:01:16.640
the last ridges of the Apennines taper out, the&nbsp;
Alpine arc takes over. From this narrow coastal

00:01:16.640 --> 00:01:22.640
pass, the ridgelines quickly spread out across&nbsp;
southeastern France, filling a 180‑kilometer‑wide

00:01:22.640 --> 00:01:29.120
mountain corridor that gradually bends eastwards&nbsp;
around the Italian Po Valley. In this southwestern

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:35.360
section of the Alps, near the high reaches of the&nbsp;
pyramidal Monviso, the Po, Italy’s longest river,

00:01:35.360 --> 00:01:41.600
is born. From here it flows eastward, draining&nbsp;
almost the entire southern flank of the Alps

00:01:41.600 --> 00:01:47.600
before emptying into the Adriatic Sea. This river&nbsp;
constitutes one of the 4 major drainage basins

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:54.000
of the Alps, with the Rhone, Rhine and Danube&nbsp;
each draining one of the cardinal directions.

00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:59.520
The French–Italian border along the main chain&nbsp;
of the Alps is lined with parks on both sides

00:01:59.520 --> 00:02:04.720
that protect these high‑alpine landscapes and&nbsp;
their fragile ecosystems of conifer forests

00:02:04.720 --> 00:02:09.840
in the valleys to lichens clinging to the&nbsp;
highest ridges. At the same time however,

00:02:09.840 --> 00:02:14.640
France walks a tightrope here, operating&nbsp;
some of the largest ski resorts on Earth,

00:02:14.640 --> 00:02:21.840
like Les Trois Vallées, La Plagne or Tignes,&nbsp;
right between these protected high‑mountain areas.

00:02:21.840 --> 00:02:26.400
The tallest summit of this region is&nbsp;
called the Barre des Écrins, which up

00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:32.000
until the French Annexation of Savoir in&nbsp;
1860, and with it, the Mont Blanc Massif,

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:39.120
stood as the tallest mountain of France. At 4101&nbsp;
meters above sea level it allows for spectacular

00:02:39.120 --> 00:02:44.400
views into the neighbouring region, where most&nbsp;
of the Alps most famous landmarks can be found.

00:02:44.400 --> 00:02:48.320
Home to many of the highest and&nbsp;
most iconic mountains in the Alps,

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:53.840
including the Mont Blanc, the Dufourspitze and&nbsp;
the Matterhorn, it also holds the quintessential

00:02:53.840 --> 00:03:00.160
alpine villages and landscapes most people think&nbsp;
of when they imagine the Alps. Shared by France,

00:03:00.160 --> 00:03:04.800
Italy and a large part of Switzerland,&nbsp;
its mountain pastures helped give rise

00:03:04.800 --> 00:03:10.160
to a thriving chocolate and cheese industry, but&nbsp;
not everything here is as harmonious as it looks.

00:03:10.160 --> 00:03:14.960
Since the 19th century, conflicting views&nbsp;
of the exact border have turned the summit

00:03:14.960 --> 00:03:20.080
of Mont Blanc into a sensitive topic. France&nbsp;
claims full authority over the mountain,

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:25.520
pointing to its role in building infrastructure,&nbsp;
running rescue services and controlling access

00:03:25.520 --> 00:03:30.880
to the summit. Italy, however, argues that&nbsp;
the border should follow the main watershed,

00:03:30.880 --> 00:03:35.200
which would make the highest peak of the Mont&nbsp;
Blanc massif a shared summit, as is the case

00:03:35.200 --> 00:03:40.160
for most other major peaks along the Alps.
France's claim is reinforced by the presence

00:03:40.160 --> 00:03:45.280
of Chamonix, a village on the western foothills&nbsp;
of the mountain which acts as the mountaineering

00:03:45.280 --> 00:03:50.240
gateway to central Europe’s highest peak.&nbsp;
Chamonix is so closely tied to the history

00:03:50.240 --> 00:03:55.120
of mountain sports that it also became&nbsp;
the birthplace of the Winter Olympics,

00:03:55.120 --> 00:04:01.280
with the very first edition held here in 1924.
Following the French and Swiss border with Italy

00:04:01.280 --> 00:04:07.200
eastwards, we encounter many more of the Alps’&nbsp;
most iconic peaks. The pyramidical summit of

00:04:07.200 --> 00:04:12.240
the Matterhorn, nicknamed “the Mountain of&nbsp;
Mountains” has long been the emblem of the

00:04:12.240 --> 00:04:18.240
mountain range as a whole, while summits like the&nbsp;
Dufourspitze are a point of national Swiss pride,

00:04:18.240 --> 00:04:23.680
with its summit lying entirely on Swiss soil.&nbsp;
The peak is named after the Swiss general and

00:04:23.680 --> 00:04:29.120
cartographer Guillaume-Henri Dufour, who spent&nbsp;
two decades leading a detailed triangulation of

00:04:29.120 --> 00:04:35.360
the country. The result was a 25‑sheet series&nbsp;
that, for the first time, showed every summit,

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:40.480
glacier and valley of Switzerland with&nbsp;
striking accuracy. The set of maps was

00:04:40.480 --> 00:04:46.640
so influential that it helped shape the very&nbsp;
idea of Switzerland as a unified alpine nation.

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:50.960
During the period when Dufour’s map&nbsp;
series was being created, many of the

00:04:50.960 --> 00:04:56.560
most dangerous mountains of the north‑western&nbsp;
Alps were climbed for the first time. Swiss,

00:04:56.560 --> 00:05:01.920
Austrian, French and British alpinists&nbsp;
pushed their way up dozens of glaciated

00:05:02.480 --> 00:05:07.520
four‑thousand‑meter summits in what became&nbsp;
known as the golden age of alpinism. It began

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:12.080
with the first ascent of the Wetterhorn,&nbsp;
towering above the village of Grindelwald,

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:17.760
and over the next ten years led to the first&nbsp;
successful climbs of many of these ice giants,

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:22.640
culminating in the first ascent&nbsp;
of the Matterhorn in 1865.

00:05:22.640 --> 00:05:28.400
At first, mountaineers chose the most accessible&nbsp;
routes, but as time went on, equipment improved

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:34.240
and the drive for more challenging terrain grew,&nbsp;
the harder lines began to look more attractive.

00:05:34.240 --> 00:05:39.120
Several of the peaks first climbed during the&nbsp;
golden age of alpinism have especially daunting

00:05:39.120 --> 00:05:42.856
routes on their north faces, and together&nbsp;
they became known as

00:05:42.856 --> 00:05:45.212
the “Great North Faces of the Alps"

00:05:45.399 --> 00:05:47.920
These dramatic walls rise above some of

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:53.280
the largest surviving icefields of the Alps.&nbsp;
Contained behind the Eiger and surrounded by

00:05:53.280 --> 00:06:00.240
many more jewels of the Bernese Alps, the ocean of&nbsp;
ice extends for over 22 kilometers along the south

00:06:00.240 --> 00:06:06.720
face of the Bernese Alps, forming the longest&nbsp;
and largest glacier of the Alps. Centuries ago,

00:06:06.720 --> 00:06:12.720
before the advent of mechanical refrigeration,&nbsp;
the glacier was cut up and exported across Europe,

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:18.560
but in modern times, the ice has become a lot&nbsp;
more cared for. Throughout the last 100 years,

00:06:18.560 --> 00:06:22.400
the Bernese Alps have lost around&nbsp;
half of the total glacier cover,

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:27.760
and continuous melting thins out the&nbsp;
remaining glaciers by roughly 70 cm per year,

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:33.840
creating an uncertain future for these iceworlds.
During the peak of the last Ice Age, the glacial

00:06:33.840 --> 00:06:39.920
cover extended far beyond today's limits and&nbsp;
the slow but grinding flow of these ice masses

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:44.960
eroded deep basins around the edge of&nbsp;
the main Alpine chain. As the glaciers

00:06:44.960 --> 00:06:50.640
retreated from these margins, meltwater of&nbsp;
the remnants slowly filled up the depressions

00:06:50.640 --> 00:06:55.840
carved out by the ice, creating some of the&nbsp;
most picturesque mountain lakes in the world.

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:02.000
Especially on the southern borders of Switzerland,&nbsp;
Lake Maggiore, Lake Lugano and Lake Como lie in a

00:07:02.000 --> 00:07:07.280
narrow transition zone between the harsh alpine&nbsp;
and the soft mediterranean climate, resulting

00:07:07.280 --> 00:07:12.480
in an epitome of tranquility, where densely&nbsp;
forested mountain slopes are rising steeply

00:07:12.480 --> 00:07:18.880
above terraced gardens, citrus trees and medieval&nbsp;
architecture in the mirroring lake surface.

00:07:18.880 --> 00:07:25.200
From the easternmost of these lakes, Lake Como,&nbsp;
a line drawn northwards through Liechtenstein and to

00:07:25.200 --> 00:07:30.560
Lake Constance marks the end of the Western Alps.
But before we get into the second part of this

00:07:30.560 --> 00:07:34.418
video, did you know that these Alps aren’t the&nbsp;
only mountain range in the world

00:07:34.418 --> 00:07:39.029
called “Alps”. The main mountains of the South Island of New Zealand

00:07:39.029 --> 00:07:41.360
are called the&nbsp;Southern Alps, which is something I only found out

00:07:41.360 --> 00:07:46.560
after playing the Mountain Ranges game in the app&nbsp;
Jordglobe geography, the sponsor of this video.

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:51.280
Chances are, if you are enjoying this video, you&nbsp;
already enjoy looking at maps and learning about

00:07:51.280 --> 00:07:56.400
the geographical intricacies of our planet a&nbsp;
bit more than the average person. Jordglobe

00:07:56.400 --> 00:08:01.760
Geography is here to turn that into a game,&nbsp;
where you visually study countries, cities,

00:08:01.760 --> 00:08:08.160
flags, states, capitals, even planets and much&nbsp;
more. I personally especially like the daily

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:14.080
quiz which ties history and contemporary facts&nbsp;
together with Geography, or the 1v1 duel mode,

00:08:14.080 --> 00:08:18.800
where you can challenge friends and online&nbsp;
users in a global battle of general knowledge.

00:08:18.800 --> 00:08:22.880
So, if you want a more interactive way to&nbsp;
deepen the knowledge of the topics that we’re

00:08:22.880 --> 00:08:27.200
already discussing on this channel, download&nbsp;
Jordglobe Geography for free on Google Play

00:08:27.200 --> 00:08:31.840
or the App Store. I’ll leave the link in the&nbsp;
description below and now, let's continue with

00:08:31.840 --> 00:08:36.400
the second half of the Alps.
Chapter 2: The Eastern Alps

00:08:36.400 --> 00:08:41.360
Leaving the enormous peaks of the Western Alps&nbsp;
behind, the mountain range as a whole becomes

00:08:41.360 --> 00:08:47.360
a bit more mellow. While the Western Alps boast&nbsp;
a total of 81 summits surpassing the 4000 meter

00:08:47.360 --> 00:08:53.680
mark, the Eastern Alps only have one: the Piz&nbsp;
Bernina near the alpine resort of St. Moritz.

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:59.440
Its name makes it immediately identifiable as&nbsp;
southern Swiss, because the prefix “Piz” is

00:08:59.440 --> 00:09:05.313
used for many major summits in Romansh, the fourth&nbsp;
national language of Switzerland that is prevalent&nbsp;here.

00:09:05.317 --> 00:09:08.160
Just&nbsp;one ridgeline behind the glamour of the Engadin

00:09:08.160 --> 00:09:14.720
Valley, the small village of Juf is tucked away in&nbsp;
a narrow side valley. At first glance, the homes

00:09:14.720 --> 00:09:21.280
of its roughly thirty inhabitants might seem quite&nbsp;
unremarkable, but at an elevation of about 2,100

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:27.440
meters, Juf is actually the highest permanently&nbsp;
inhabited settlement in the entire Alpine arc.

00:09:27.440 --> 00:09:31.680
That elevation may not sound particularly&nbsp;
impressive at first, especially when you

00:09:31.680 --> 00:09:36.640
think of countries like Bolivia, Ecuador or&nbsp;
Mexico, where national capitals with millions

00:09:36.640 --> 00:09:42.720
of inhabitants sit far above 2,100 meters. But&nbsp;
that is not really a fair comparison to the Alps.

00:09:42.720 --> 00:09:47.680
Because of the Alps' more northerly position,&nbsp;
they experience a generally colder climate,

00:09:47.680 --> 00:09:53.440
and their steep, rocky slopes create a sharp upper&nbsp;
limit for forests and meadows, especially in the

00:09:53.440 --> 00:09:59.200
northern part of the range. Above the tree line,&nbsp;
villages are far more exposed to wind, cold and

00:09:59.200 --> 00:10:04.320
snow, which makes permanent settlement at higher&nbsp;
elevations nearly impossible. Yet, in the pockets

00:10:04.320 --> 00:10:09.120
where it is possible, the jagged topography&nbsp;
has resulted in some strange border anomalies.

00:10:09.680 --> 00:10:14.880
Following the German–Austrian border eastwards&nbsp;
from Lake Constance, a lone valley with several

00:10:14.880 --> 00:10:20.720
villages strung together on a single road is&nbsp;
surrounded by mountains on almost all sides.

00:10:20.720 --> 00:10:25.520
These villages are certainly within Austrian&nbsp;
Territory, yet the road connecting them only

00:10:25.520 --> 00:10:31.760
leads to Germany. This paradoxically makes them&nbsp;
an Austrian enclave, within Austrian territory,

00:10:31.760 --> 00:10:37.280
at least when looking at road transport.
Just 40 kilometers northward, a second border

00:10:37.280 --> 00:10:42.080
peculiarity reveals itself between Austria&nbsp;
and Germany, with a little island of Austria

00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:47.760
sticking out of the mainland, only touching the&nbsp;
continuous Austria at a single geometric point,

00:10:47.760 --> 00:10:52.640
creating something very close to a quadripoint&nbsp;
border. There has only been a single instance in

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:58.720
mapped history where a true quadripoint existed,&nbsp;
which lasted for eight months between Chad,

00:10:58.720 --> 00:11:04.000
Nigeria, British Cameroon and French&nbsp;
Cameroon in central Africa. But for now

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.360
this is the closest that we have, even if it&nbsp;
is shared by just two countries and not four.

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:14.240
Following the alpine foothills further east,&nbsp;
dozens of mountain lakes across the German and

00:11:14.240 --> 00:11:18.640
Austrian Pre-Alps collect the meltwater&nbsp;
from the northern flanks of the Alps,

00:11:18.640 --> 00:11:23.680
similar to how lakes Maggiore, Lugano, Como&nbsp;
and Garda store the southern meltwater.

00:11:23.680 --> 00:11:28.880
The most photogenic one of these is the little Lake&nbsp;
Hallstatt, whose iconic church spire stands in

00:11:28.880 --> 00:11:33.920
front of the magnificent forested slopes of the&nbsp;
Dachstein, a mountain range containing one of the

00:11:33.920 --> 00:11:39.200
most spectacular natural phenomena of the Alps.
Deep inside this mountain range, a fissure

00:11:39.200 --> 00:11:44.000
dating back to when tectonic forces folded&nbsp;
up the Alps has been further washed out by

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:50.320
the headwaters of the Salzach, creating one of the&nbsp;
most intricate cave networks in the entire world. Today,

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:56.640
a network of 42 kilometers, or 26 miles,&nbsp;
is buried deep inside the limestone massif,

00:11:56.640 --> 00:12:02.320
of which the first kilometer is accessible to&nbsp;
visitors. The system’s multiple entrances create

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:07.600
a powerful chimney effect, with air constantly&nbsp;
circulating through the mountain and keeping the

00:12:07.600 --> 00:12:13.840
caves at near‑freezing temperatures year‑round.&nbsp;
Water seeping in through the soluble limestone

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:18.960
freezes almost instantly when it meets the&nbsp;
cold air currents, forming mesmerizing ice

00:12:18.960 --> 00:12:24.320
pillars at the entrances and helping to&nbsp;
create the largest ice cave in the world.

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:29.360
Standing even taller than the rocky Dachstein,&nbsp;
and located almost in the center of the Eastern

00:12:29.360 --> 00:12:35.440
Alps, Grossglockner, with nearly 3,800&nbsp;
meters above sea level is the highest mountain in

00:12:35.440 --> 00:12:41.760
Austria. Since its first ascent in 1800, it&nbsp;
has been a major alpine tourism destination,

00:12:41.760 --> 00:12:46.800
and today a total of around 30 ascent routes&nbsp;
have been mapped across its countless ridges,

00:12:46.800 --> 00:12:52.400
chutes, glaciers and rock faces. From the&nbsp;
summit, its exceptional topographic prominence

00:12:52.400 --> 00:12:57.600
and isolation allow for sweeping views over&nbsp;
the surrounding Hohe Tauern National Park,

00:12:57.600 --> 00:13:03.200
the largest national park in the Alps and a vast&nbsp;
high‑mountain barrier at the heart of the range.

00:13:03.200 --> 00:13:07.520
Throughout this whole section of the Alps,&nbsp;
the countless ridges and valleys are primarily

00:13:07.520 --> 00:13:13.280
oriented in an east-west direction, which has&nbsp;
complicated the traversing of the Alps ever since

00:13:13.280 --> 00:13:18.640
people tried to make this part of Europe their&nbsp;
home. Today there are only a few major passes

00:13:18.640 --> 00:13:25.280
which allow for high capacity north-south travel.&nbsp;
While marvels of modern engineering like the 57km

00:13:25.280 --> 00:13:30.640
long Gotthard Base Tunnel provide a significant&nbsp;
shortcut for rail traffic, heavy vehicle roads

00:13:30.640 --> 00:13:35.840
are rare due to many passes relying on steep&nbsp;
hairpin turns which make it impractical for

00:13:35.840 --> 00:13:41.040
larger trucks to pass. Only a handful of mountain&nbsp;
saddles are mellow enough for trucks to handle

00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:47.040
and the Brenner Pass at the Austrian Italian&nbsp;
Border is the most famous and busy one. Nearly

00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:51.680
one third of all road freight passes the Alps&nbsp;
through this narrow corridor, and its benefits

00:13:51.680 --> 00:13:56.880
have been known to human civilizations for&nbsp;
millennia now. Even during ancient Roman times,

00:13:56.880 --> 00:14:02.880
armies and traders used the Brenner Pass to access&nbsp;
central Europe from the Italian peninsula, but it

00:14:02.880 --> 00:14:08.400
is far from the only route that people utilized.
Following the main traffic artery from the Brenner

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:14.880
Pass southwards, we approach the South Tyrolean&nbsp;
Capital of Bolzano and to our left, the final

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:19.760
region of our journey across the Alps rises above&nbsp;
the valleys and stretches all the way to the

00:14:19.760 --> 00:14:26.560
eastern Po Valley: The Dolomites. Characterized&nbsp;
by rugged pale rock outcrops that are rising

00:14:26.560 --> 00:14:32.720
sharply over the lush green meadows with tranquil&nbsp;
villages and hiking paths. This color stands in

00:14:32.720 --> 00:14:38.000
stark contrast to the darker granite towers of&nbsp;
Switzerland, hinting at the various rocklayers

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:43.120
that have been uplifted during the creation of the&nbsp;
Alps. The Dolomites have been named after the rock

00:14:43.120 --> 00:14:48.800
type dolomite which is a sedimentary carbonate&nbsp;
rock, originating from the seabed of the ancient

00:14:48.800 --> 00:14:54.320
Tethys Ocean and its distinct fracture planes&nbsp;
allow for the formation of the steep mountain

00:14:54.320 --> 00:15:00.480
faces, angled ridge lines and cliffs, which&nbsp;
make the towers of the Dolomites so iconic.

00:15:00.480 --> 00:15:05.200
Where the area truly shines however is during&nbsp;
the winter, when millions of mountain sport

00:15:05.200 --> 00:15:12.160
enthusiasts flock into the many ski resorts of&nbsp;
the dolomites. Starting in 1974, 9 of these ski

00:15:12.160 --> 00:15:17.520
resorts formed a union among themselves, adding&nbsp;
cross resort lifts to connect the slopes and

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:24.160
villages, with a total of 7 more having been added&nbsp;
since. Together this Dolomiti Superski area now

00:15:24.160 --> 00:15:31.360
covers a total of 1246 slope kilometers, with over&nbsp;
half of them being connected to each other and all

00:15:31.360 --> 00:15:37.014
of them being accessible with a single pass, making it the largest ski resort on the planet

00:15:37.014 --> 00:15:39.775
As a global winter sports hotspot, the Dolomites

00:15:39.775 --> 00:15:44.800
will get the honor to host the Winter Olympics for&nbsp;
the second time their history. Together with the city

00:15:44.800 --> 00:15:51.440
of Milano, Cortina d'Ampezzo will invite the world&nbsp;
for the 2026 winter olympics, to continue a long

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:57.440
lasting dominance of hosting the Winter Olympics&nbsp;
in the Alps. Of the 27 winter olympics which have

00:15:57.440 --> 00:16:04.240
been held or are currently planned, since the&nbsp;
first edition in 1924, 45% of them have been held

00:16:04.240 --> 00:16:10.640
in the French, Italian, Swiss, German or Austrian&nbsp;
sections of the Alps. This goes to show just how

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:16.080
culturally significant the Alps are, not just&nbsp;
for Central Europe, but for the world as a whole.

00:16:16.080 --> 00:16:21.040
Farther east, the mountains gradually lose&nbsp;
height and splinter into the Julian Alps of

00:16:21.040 --> 00:16:26.320
Slovenia before melting into the Dinaric&nbsp;
Alps and the open lowlands of the Great

00:16:26.320 --> 00:16:31.440
Hungarian Plain. Here, the last Alpine&nbsp;
foothills give way to rolling farmland,

00:16:31.440 --> 00:16:38.960
marking the quiet end of a mountain arc that began&nbsp;
so abruptly at the shores of the Mediterranean.

00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:44.240
As a whole, this mountain range encapsulates&nbsp;
what it means for natural spaces to serve its

00:16:44.240 --> 00:16:50.400
community, as a place to rest and explore, as a&nbsp;
playground and a retreat. While its natural beauty

00:16:50.400 --> 00:16:55.440
is at the mercy of our pursuit for development,&nbsp;
there are still countless untouched pockets of

00:16:55.440 --> 00:17:00.960
wilderness left to explore, enjoy and protect.
If you want to explore more of the world’s great

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:06.160
mountain ranges, you can continue with these&nbsp;
videos on the Caucasus or the Rocky Mountains.

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:10.480
